data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or `ThreadAbortException` — so no abort migration is needed. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep`, which all work identically in .NET 8.

That said, for a modern .NET 8 migration, consider replacing raw threads with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll`:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
    });
}
```

This gives you built-in concurrency control, cancellation support via `CancellationToken`, and better thread pool usage — but it's a modernization improvement, not a required migration fix.
